Here is a complete, practical explanation of Inertia.js for a developer coming from a Next.js/React background.

---

## 1. What Inertia.js Is and How It Works (Conceptual Model)

Inertia.js is **not a framework** -- it is a glue layer that connects a server-side framework (Laravel, Rails, etc.) to a frontend component library (React, Vue, or Svelte). The mental model is:

**"Build a classic server-rendered monolith, but replace Blade/PHP templates with React components."**

Your Laravel app still owns routing, controllers, middleware, auth, and data fetching. Instead of returning an HTML view, controllers return an Inertia response that names a React component and passes it data as props.

**How the protocol works:**

- **First page load:** Laravel renders a full HTML page containing a root `<div>` with a JSON-encoded payload (the component name + its props). React hydrates from that.
- **Subsequent navigation:** When you click an Inertia `<Link>`, Inertia intercepts the click, makes an XHR request to the server instead of a full page load. The server detects the `X-Inertia` header and returns a JSON response (not HTML) containing the new component name and props. Inertia swaps the old React component for the new one and updates `history.pushState`. No full page reload ever happens after the initial load.

The key insight: **the server is always the source of truth for what component to render and what data it receives.** There is no client-side router deciding what to show.

---

## 2. Data Flow from Laravel Controller to React Component

**Laravel controller (`app/Http/Controllers/PostController.php`):**
```php
public function index()
{
    return Inertia::render('Posts/Index', [
        'posts' => Post::with('author')->paginate(10),
        'filters' => request()->only(['search', 'status']),
    ]);
}
```

**React component (`resources/js/Pages/Posts/Index.jsx`):**
```jsx
export default function Index({ posts, filters }) {
    return (
        <div>
            <h1>Posts</h1>
            {posts.data.map(post => (
                <div key={post.id}>
                    <h2>{post.title}</h2>
                    <p>By {post.author.name}</p>
                </div>
            ))}
        </div>
    );
}
```

That is it. No API endpoint, no `fetch()`, no Axios, no TanStack Query, no loading states for initial data. The props arrive already resolved when the component mounts. Laravel's `Inertia::render()` is the equivalent of `return view('posts.index', [...])` but targets a React component instead of a Blade template.

**Routes are standard Laravel web routes** (`routes/web.php`), not API routes:
```php
Route::get('/posts', [PostController::class, 'index']);
Route::post('/posts', [PostController::class, 'store']);
```

---

## 3. How It Differs from a Traditional Decoupled SPA

| Aspect | Traditional SPA (Next.js + API) | Inertia.js |
|---|---|---|
| **Routing** | Client-side (React Router / Next.js file-based) | Server-side (Laravel `routes/web.php`) |
| **Data fetching** | `fetch`/Axios/TanStack Query to API endpoints | Props passed directly from controller -- no API calls |
| **API layer** | Required (REST or GraphQL) | Not needed -- controllers return Inertia responses |
| **Auth** | Token-based (JWT, Sanctum tokens), stored in localStorage/cookies | Session-based, standard Laravel session cookies |
| **CORS** | Must be configured | Not an issue -- same origin |
| **State management** | Often need Redux/Zustand/TanStack Query cache | Server is the state -- much less client-side state needed |
| **Deployment** | Separate frontend + backend deploys | Single monolith deploy |
| **SEO/SSR** | Built into Next.js | Optional SSR via Inertia's SSR module |

The fundamental shift: in a traditional SPA, the frontend decides what data it needs and asks the API. In Inertia, the **server decides what data the page needs** and hands it to the component. There is no "loading" state for page data because it arrives with the page.

---

## 4. How Forms Work (useForm Hook)

Inertia provides a `useForm` hook that manages form state, submission, validation errors, and processing state in one place:

```jsx
import { useForm } from '@inertiajs/react'

export default function CreatePost() {
    const { data, setData, post, processing, errors, reset } = useForm({
        title: '',
        body: '',
    });

    function submit(e) {
        e.preventDefault();
        post('/posts', {
            preserveScroll: true,
            onSuccess: () => reset(),
        });
    }

    return (
        <form onSubmit={submit}>
            <input
                type="text"
                value={data.title}
                onChange={e => setData('title', e.target.value)}
            />
            {errors.title && <div className="text-red-500">{errors.title}</div>}

            <textarea
                value={data.body}
                onChange={e => setData('body', e.target.value)}
            />
            {errors.body && <div className="text-red-500">{errors.body}</div>}

            <button type="submit" disabled={processing}>
                {processing ? 'Saving...' : 'Create Post'}
            </button>
        </form>
    );
}
```

**Server side (`PostController`):**
```php
public function store(Request $request)
{
    $request->validate([
        'title' => ['required', 'max:255'],
        'body' => ['required'],
    ]);

    Post::create($request->all());

    return redirect()->route('posts.index');
}
```

Key things to understand about this flow:

- **Validation errors are automatic.** When Laravel validation fails, it redirects back with errors. Inertia intercepts this and populates `errors` on the form object. You never check for a 422 status code yourself.
- **No separate error handling code.** The redirect-based flow means your React component just reads `errors.title`, `errors.body` etc.
- **`processing` tracks submission state** -- use it to disable submit buttons.
- **`post`, `put`, `patch`, `delete`** methods are available for different HTTP verbs.
- **File uploads work automatically** -- Inertia converts to FormData when files are detected.
- Inertia v2 also provides a declarative `<Form>` component that works more like plain HTML forms (using `name` attributes instead of `setData`).

---

## 5. How Page Navigation Works (No Full Page Reloads)

**The `<Link>` component:**
```jsx
import { Link } from '@inertiajs/react'

// Basic navigation
<Link href="/posts">All Posts</Link>

// With method and data
<Link href={`/posts/${post.id}`} method="delete" as="button">
    Delete
</Link>

// Preserve scroll position
<Link href="/posts?page=2" preserveScroll>Page 2</Link>

// Preserve component state (useful for forms)
<Link href="/users?search=john" preserveState>Search</Link>
```

**Programmatic navigation:**
```jsx
import { router } from '@inertiajs/react'

// Navigate programmatically
router.visit('/posts')
router.post('/posts', formData)
router.delete(`/posts/${id}`)

// With options
router.visit('/dashboard', {
    preserveScroll: true,
    preserveState: true,
    only: ['notifications'],  // partial reload -- only fetch these props
})
```

**Partial reloads** are a key performance feature: you can request only specific props from the server instead of all the data for the page. This is useful for refreshing a notification count without re-fetching the entire page's data.

Under the hood, every `<Link>` click becomes an XHR. The server returns JSON like:
```json
{
    "component": "Posts/Index",
    "props": { "posts": [...], "filters": {...} },
    "url": "/posts",
    "version": "abc123"
}
```
Inertia swaps in the new React component, updates the browser URL via `history.pushState`, and the user sees an instant page transition.

---

## 6. Key Pros and Cons for Someone Coming from Next.js/React

### Pros

- **No API layer to build or maintain.** This is the biggest time savings. No REST routes, no serializers, no API versioning, no Axios config, no TanStack Query setup. Data goes directly from database query to React prop.
- **Server-side validation only.** You write validation rules once in Laravel. Errors flow back to your form automatically. No duplicating validation in Zod/Yup on the frontend.
- **Authentication is trivial.** Session-based auth with Laravel's built-in system. No token management, no refresh token flows, no protected route HOCs checking localStorage.
- **Much less client-side state.** Since every page visit returns fresh data from the server, you rarely need Redux, Zustand, or a query cache. The server is your single source of truth.
- **Laravel's full ecosystem.** Eloquent ORM, queues, notifications, file storage, authorization policies -- all available directly in controllers that feed your React pages.
- **Simpler deployment.** One codebase, one deploy, one server.
- **Familiar React DX.** You still write normal React components, use hooks, use your component libraries (shadcn/ui, etc.).

### Cons

- **No client-side routing control.** In Next.js you can do instant client-side transitions with prefetched data. In Inertia, every navigation hits the server. On slow connections or distant servers, this can feel sluggish compared to a true SPA with cached data.
- **Tight coupling to Laravel.** Your React components implicitly depend on the shape of data your controllers pass. Switching to a different backend later means rewriting how every page gets its data. No clean API contract.
- **No independent frontend deployment.** Cannot deploy frontend and backend independently. No CDN-first architecture.
- **Limited React ecosystem compatibility.** Features like React Suspense, streaming SSR (`renderToReadableStream`), and React Server Components are not supported. Inertia uses `renderToString` for SSR.
- **Props embedded in HTML.** On the initial page load, all page props are JSON-encoded into the HTML. If a page has a lot of data, this bloats the HTML document size noticeably.
- **Smaller community than Next.js.** Fewer tutorials, fewer Stack Overflow answers, fewer third-party integrations. When you hit an edge case, you may be on your own.
- **No offline / optimistic updates pattern.** Without a client-side cache layer (like TanStack Query), patterns like optimistic updates are harder. Every mutation round-trips to the server.
- **Mobile API reuse.** If you later need a mobile app or third-party API consumers, you will need to build a separate API layer anyway, since Inertia responses are not consumable by non-Inertia clients.

---

## 7. How Auth Works with Inertia + Breeze (Session-Based, No Tokens)

Laravel Breeze with the Inertia/React stack scaffolds a complete auth system out of the box. It is **entirely session-based** -- no JWTs, no OAuth tokens, no Sanctum API tokens.

**How login works (`AuthenticatedSessionController`):**
```php
// Show the login page (renders a React component)
public function create(): Response
{
    return Inertia::render('Auth/Login', [
        'canResetPassword' => Route::has('password.request'),
        'status' => session('status'),
    ]);
}

// Handle the login form submission
public function store(LoginRequest $request): RedirectResponse
{
    $request->authenticate();           // Validates credentials
    $request->session()->regenerate();   // Prevents session fixation
    return redirect()->intended(route('dashboard', absolute: false));
}

// Logout
public function destroy(Request $request): RedirectResponse
{
    Auth::guard('web')->logout();
    $request->session()->invalidate();
    $request->session()->regenerateToken();
    return redirect('/');
}
```

**How the authenticated user reaches React components:**

The `HandleInertiaRequests` middleware shares the auth user globally:
```php
class HandleInertiaRequests extends Middleware
{
    public function share(Request $request)
    {
        return array_merge(parent::share($request), [
            'auth.user' => fn () => $request->user()
                ? $request->user()->only('id', 'name', 'email')
                : null,
        ]);
    }
}
```

Every React component can then access the user via `usePage()`:
```jsx
import { usePage } from '@inertiajs/react'

export default function Nav() {
    const { auth } = usePage().props;

    return (
        <nav>
            {auth.user ? (
                <span>Hello, {auth.user.name}</span>
            ) : (
                <Link href="/login">Log in</Link>
            )}
        </nav>
    );
}
```

**Why this matters for a Next.js developer:** There is no `getServerSideProps` auth check, no middleware.ts edge function, no NextAuth config, no session provider wrapping your app. Laravel middleware protects routes on the server. If a user is not authenticated, they get redirected before any React component ever renders. The auth state is always server-authoritative.

---

## 8. Gotchas and Learning Curve Issues

**Mental model shift (the biggest one):** Coming from Next.js, you are used to the frontend being in charge -- the frontend decides what data to fetch, when to refetch, how to cache it. In Inertia, the server is in charge. You need to stop thinking "I'll fetch this data" and start thinking "the controller will hand me this data." This is the single hardest adjustment.

**Every navigation is a server round-trip.** There is no client-side route cache. If a user navigates from `/posts` to `/posts/1` and back to `/posts`, that is three server requests. Inertia v2 added prefetching and caching features to mitigate this, but it is fundamentally different from a client-side router with cached query results.

**Debugging data issues.** When props are wrong, you debug in the Laravel controller, not in React DevTools network tab. There is no "API response" to inspect -- you need to check what `Inertia::render()` is passing.

**No React Server Components or Suspense.** If you are used to RSC patterns from Next.js 13+, those do not exist here. Inertia uses `renderToString` for SSR, not streaming.

**Large page props blow up HTML size.** If a controller passes a large dataset (e.g., 500 rows with nested relationships), all of that is JSON-encoded into the initial HTML `<div id="app" data-page="...">`. This can cause slow initial renders. Use pagination and partial reloads to mitigate.

**Form state management is different from React Hook Form.** If you are used to React Hook Form or Formik, the `useForm` hook will feel familiar but not identical. The key difference: validation comes from the server after submission, not from client-side schemas. There is no Zod/Yup integration. Inertia v2.3+ added "Precognition" for real-time server-side validation, but it requires a specific Laravel setup.

**No easy way to share state between pages.** Since each page visit gets fresh props from the server, there is no persistent client-side store across navigations by default. If you need cross-page state (like a shopping cart), you either use Laravel sessions (server-side) or add a lightweight client-side store yourself.

**TypeScript support requires extra work.** You need to manually type your page props to match what Laravel controllers return. There is no automatic type generation from controller to component (though community packages like `laravel-data` with TypeScript transformer can help).

**Testing straddles two worlds.** Unit testing React components is normal (Vitest/Jest), but integration testing the full flow means testing Laravel controllers, Inertia responses, and React rendering together. There is no single testing story like Next.js with Playwright hitting one app.

---

